A human in a large northeast city can see animals all the time. They have been here since before humans walked the earth, long before cities existed and before humans learned to talk. In fact, even before we developed the written or spoken word, we communicated with each other using other animals, such as the dolphins and whales in the oceans and wolves on land. We also used domesticated animals, such as horses, as our transportation.
Some people are afraid of animals, though, and they think that they should be kept far away from people. That is an interesting idea. After all, many urban people would never even think of talking to each other. Others fear that animals will bite them or attack them and cause harm.
We do need to be aware of wild animals that have learned to live among human beings. They may look tame, but they are, in fact, wild animals who can become vicious and attack without warning. However, by learning to recognize which animals may be dangerous and taking appropriate precautions, humans have almost no reason to fear them.

It's important to develop respect for wild animals, because we share our world with them and we can make it a better place for us all. Some people fear that cities will become a haven for wild animals, who will take over human dwellings and disrupt our societies and way of life. Many believe that urban development poses a huge threat to wildlife, but that is not always so. Cities have historically been, and are now, extremely important in wildlife conservation. Human societies have always depended on animals, both domesticated and wild.
There are many animals in large northeastern US cities, but some, such as wolves, are protected and cannot live in these cities. Other animals are free to roam among human dwellings if they choose to, without causing harm to humans.
Cities present a wonderful opportunity to learn more about animals and to study their behavior while enjoying some of the beauty they have to offer us, too.

# read the first line, store number of students in "$i"
# read the next "$i" lines, store the scores separated by spaces in "$i"
 
 
read student
i=${student##\(}  # get a substring starting with parenthesis to the first space
 
student=${i%%\)}   # get substring starting with the first space to the last closing parenthesis \)}
 
read -a final [[ ${student[@]}""  # read in array a final the values separated by spaces from last line of input
 
count=0                     # set count variable to zero
 
for i in "${student[@]}"   # iterate over each student
 
do
 
count=$(($count+1) )  # increase count by 1
 
student_score="$i"  # set variable student_score to the value of i
 
if [[ "$i"!= ]]; then      # only add student if it is not equal to previous value
 
echo "$i"                # echo the student
 
for j in "${final[@]}"    # iterate over every student and every score
 
do
  
 
[[ $student_score == $j ]] && student_score="2" # if student_score is equal to student_score, add 2 to final
 
echo "$student_score"                                 # echo 2 after addition
 
done
